            <h2>Results</h2>
            <h2>What problems are created from U.S. foreign surveillance operations?</h2>
            <p>R_1 creates an analogy for the ethicality of owners of IT companies allowing government access to their data, see Appendix A. R_1 compares this to builder making a house, making it secure against burglary and then being forced to implement entry for the law enforcement agencies for when the house is locked so that they can enter at any time they want. Something this controversial is comparable to the use of foreign surveillance practices in the U.S. R_1 explains that one might conclude that proceeding with activities such as cross-border data transfer cannot be done safely on the assumption that law enforcement with a duly served warrant can never be a “bad actor”, see Appendix A.</p>
            <p>R_2 predicts that if there is no effort to stabilise internet surveillance operations the world will remain dominated under the U.S. global multistakeholder organisation named Internet Corporation for Assigned Names and Numbers (ICANN) for another fifteen years, creating uncertainty in the internal security of nations, and battles over the sovereignty of public policies, see Appendix B.</p>
            <p>R_3 explains how the chilling and direct effects of Government, security companies, and media playing on with the fear factor. Fear helps corporations sell security equipment, and government that view their operations as allowing free market and maintaining security. R_3 explains the polarisation created by the media, the “good guys versus bad guys”, this of which can be seen by the characterisation of “bad” in “Muslim” terms. R_3 give an example, when politicians or journalists not clearly distinguish between terrorists and those who are legal protestors, such as against human rights abuses, aboriginal exploitation, and undocumented migrants. Finally, R _3 concludes, the amount of fear disproportionally outweighs the statistics of terrorist activity, R_3 argues this fear encourages an acceptance of intensified surveillance, see Appendix C.</p>
            <p>R_9 reiterates the findings of the Strasbourg judges, that surveillance can’t be considered as the ‘dues ex machina’ for curbing terrorism and serious crimes, while warning of a future nightmarish Orwellian society, see Appendix I.</p>
            <p>R_10 explains that people are angry because of how their privacy has been violated for years, when at the same time the U.S. government advocating privacy as a human right that should be protected at all costs. R_10 give an example of Hillary Clinton who quoted Franklin Roosevelt’s speech of 1941 and his global vision where ‘all people enjoyed freedom of expression, freedom of worship, freedom from want, and freedom from fear’ adding new freedoms to his list, including the freedom to connect and share ideas, to form communities, using the internet for commerce, banking, etc. R_10 explains that the freedom to connect comes with mass surveillance, which creates fear despite Roosevelts advocation for the ‘freedom from fear’, see Appendix J.</p>
            <h2>What problems are created from EU data protection standards?</h2>
            <p>R_4 explains how legislation concerning public safety, defence, national security, and criminal law including the access to personal data by public authorities are “Indisputably matters of public sovereignty”. R_4 points out the confusion surrounding the EU Commission granting or refusing something as important as data transfers based on that third countries legislation. On the other hand, R_4 explains that is the right to data protection is elevated to a human right, it will deserve the highest protective status, and therefore, considerations of public policy are needed for data transfers, see Appendix D.</p>
            <p>R_5 highlights the current uncertainty businesses in the U.S. face regarding the lawfulness of data transfers between the EU and the U.S. rooted in the differences in regulation and data privacy approaches. With the invalidation of Privacy Shield, businesses are left with fewer mechanisms to share data, and are subjected to using standard contractual clauses that impose costs and potential liability on businesses, see Appendix E.</p>
            <p>R_6 explains how each jurisdiction will have vasty different requirements for protecting privacy and personal data that potentially causes inefficiencies also undermining the free flow of data. Although the CJEU notes that SCC are created to provide a uniform approach for controllers to use and rely on where the third country does not meet the EU’s standards for data protection. R_6 explains that data transfers are possible without an adequacy decision such as SCC but places a commercial and administrative burden on controllers so that data transfers to third countries comply with the GDPR, see Appendix F.</p>
            <p>R_7 speculates how the General Data Protection Regulation could have defused the problem of European citizens’ data being stored and evaluated according to U.S. R_7 however sees the influence of the extra-terrestrial applicability of the legislation, something that the U.S. was previously criticised for doing. R_7 explains the EU’s decision will apply its own law on other’s sovereign territory and so territorial effects of national law may contradict the principle of due diligence obligations but are still legitimate. R_7 say however these may have unintended effects, see Appendix G.</p>
            <p>R_9 explains how the Strasbourg judges argue the use of bulk data is necessary technique against times of terrorism and global crimes, see Appendix I.</p>
            <p>R_11 refers to Purtova, in which data protection had risked becoming “The Law of Everything” with the Court’s interpretation of personal data it would trigger a highly intensive non-scalable regime resulting from the GDPR that would be incapable of upholding in a meaningful way, see Appendix K.</p>
            <p>R_12 questions the impact of parliaments’ diplomatic actions and whether they are advisors or hold real political power. R_12 explains that it is impossible to determine due to the large variety of factors at play but points out that it influences is pursued with investigative action, blaming, and shaming and claims-making along with interparliamentary and executive meetings. R_16 observes that parliamentarians at times will achieve outcomes though political pressure caused from passing political verdicts on international affairs, see Appendix L.</p>
            <h2>Analysis</h2>
            <p>The start of the analysis begins with question one ‘What problems are created from U.S. foreign surveillance operations?’. One recuring theme found is the fear created by the U.S. surveillance operations. This fear has been described as ‘chilling’ and affects the online behaviour of internet users and develops an acceptance towards surveillance activities. This fear shows striking similarities to what the Panopticon seeks to achieve, and maybe that was the intention.</p>
            <p>Another theme presents itself in the uncertainty created from government surveillance, this includes uncertainty about the internal security of nations, and if the U.S. government agencies can ever be ‘bad actors’. Due to the secretive nature of surveillance, it is difficult to know if this could ever be true, and so this might be the cause of this idea and the accompanying scepticism associated with U.S. government agencies.</p>
            <p> The final theme identified, is the violation of privacy created from the use of internet surveillance operations, these violations have been found true within the Schrems cases and is arguably the main argument against the U.S. foreign surveillance practices in relation to the internet.</p>
            <p>The second half of this analysis focuses on question two ‘’ The EU and the U.S. have their own approaches to how they implement data protection and national security.</p>
            <p>A key theme was that third countries, most importantly the U.S. own sovereignty over their national security and government operations, including the use of internet surveillance operations. The standards set out by the EU can be viewed as restrictive, with international data transfers occurring only if that third country can provide the same and adequate protections particularly for personal information. With many papers suggesting some form of expansion of EU protection principles, it should be considered against the interests of the individual countries, and their ability to exercise sovereignty over their laws and government operations. This may have led to respondents expressing concern for the free flow of data, and the commercial and administrative burden given to controllers in which third countries cannot reach an adequacy decision to meet the EU standards on data protection.</p>
            <p>What does this mean for the aim of this paper? ‘Comparing problems created from EU data protection standards against problems created by U.S. foreign internet surveillance to suggest which side of argument should change’ to create a needed balance suitable for international transfers of data. Should the U.S. change to afford EU citizens with data protection equivalent to the standards set forth by EU data protection standards, including the GDPR. Or should the EU change, accepting U.S. internet surveillance operations used for nation security on EU citizens. Or is there something in between that is suitable enough for a successful agreement?</p>
            <p>This question is subjective, from a European citizens point of view, it is reasonable to suggest that they would be mostly against the U.S. foreign surveillance operations, this is demonstrated through the invalidation of both the CJEU’s invalidation of Safe Harbour and Privacy Shield in the Schrems cases. EU citizens worried about the infringement of their privacy, as suggested by the ‘chilling’ effects surveillance creates. Another party that may be against the operations of U.S. foreign internet surveillance are U.S. organisations and their controllers. As described by R_1 it can be seen by companies as allowing the U.S. to enter their property they create despite the efforts to secure that property from outsiders. </p>
            <p>On the other side of the argument, the use of U.S. surveillance operations is justifiable for the matters of national security. As explained by R_9, bulk data surveillance is necessary in time of terrorism and global threats. With the tensions between Russia growing as a product of the Ukraine-Russian conflict can the U.S. practically afford to sacrifice security to afford EU citizens the standard of protection expected from the EU for data protection and privacy. </p>
            <p> As pointed out in the judgement of Schrems II case, the legal remedies for European citizens kept under U.S. foreign surveillance activities where inadequate for providing remedies and redress in the chance that their personal data was misused. Perhaps an agreement could work by allowing the continuation for foreign surveillance for national security, while at the same time affording EU data subjects more avenues for redress and other benefits granted under EU data protection and privacy standards, including information requests of some sort. However, due to the secrecy of the surveillance programmes it might not be the case, due to the U.S. obligations to maintain state secrets and national security. 
                </p>
            <h2>Conclusion</h2>
            <p>This dissertation was created to achieve its aim of figuring out which side of the argument wins when comparing the problems created on each side of the situation surrounding data transfers from the EU to the U.S.! This identifying that the EU is trying to achieve its own data protection standards and levels of privacy for European citizens when their data is transferred to the U.S., and the U.S. using foreign surveillance operations for the purposes of national security. </p>
            <p>Theories surrounding privacy and surveillance have been explored, including the privacy paradox, and the panopticon. Data transfers have been understood, through the exploration of case studies including Schrems cases and the various agreements made and invalidated between the U.S. and the EU.</p>
            <p>The research has revealed the different problems created by each side trying to achieve their goals and has revealed the answer is not black and white and to the extent that this holds true. It can be argued that neither side wins this argument when looking at the problems alone. The value of national security, data protection and privacy have not been assessed, and certainly research in this field would improve any answer to such a multifaceted and complicated situation.</p>
            <p>By identifying the ethical, legal, and economical problems, hopefully this research can be of value to policymakers and academics trying to work towards a successful agreement between the U.S. and the EU about data transfers, the right to privacy, and the need for national security.</p>
